{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778556236,"nonce":"89iqTVmZRt2loLV65GfdWz+12IM=","message":"**Retraction of prior MVP-outcome comment (2026-05-11)** — the MVP as run was a dud. It trained two architectures warmup-only (no adversarial phase) and measured test-time disturbance response, which is not Δv. The d448c9d discriminator was never actually tested.\n\nΔv is a *training-method comparison*: `(peak_v(arch_adversarial) - peak_v(arch_baseline)) / peak_v(arch_baseline)`. The prediction (regulator → +Δv, tracker → ≈0) says that for the regulator, adversarial training inflates peak velocity, but for the tracker it does not — because the tracker's feedforward channel can absorb the disturbance without changing its forward motion plan.\n\nThe corrected MVP requires four models: regulator-baseline, regulator-adversarial, tracker-baseline, tracker-adversarial — then Δv is computed within each architecture's adversarial-vs-baseline pair. Implementation from `20ae797` is preserved and usable; only the analysis script and the launch protocol need updating. See `410d7ac` for the corrected design.","files":null}]}